{"title_page": "Vicky Hartzler", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Vicky Hartzler\n|image        = Vicky Hartzler 116th Congress.jpg\n|state        = [[Missouri]]\n|district     = {{ushr|MO|4|4th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Ike Skelton]]\n|successor    = \n|state_house1 = Missouri\n|district1    = 124th\n|term_start1  = 1995\n|term_end1    = 2000\n|predecessor1 = Gene Olson\n|successor1   = Rex Rector\n|birth_name   = Vicky Jo Zellmer\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1960|10|13}}\n|birth_place  = [[Archie, Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lowell Hartzler\n|children     = 1 daughter\n|education    = [[University of Missouri]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Central Missouri]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n'''Vicky Jo Hartzler''' (n\u00e9e '''Zellmer''', October 13, 1960) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MO|4}} since 2011. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], she previously served as the [[Missouri House of Representatives|Missouri State Representative]] for the 124th district from 1995 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legistorm.com/memberbio/2769/Rep_Vicky_Hartzler_MO.html|title=Representative Vicky Jo Hartzler (Vicky) (R-Missouri, 4th) \u2013 Biography from LegiStorm|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.fox4kc.com/news/sns-ap-mo--missouricongress-4thdistrict,0,6855380.story Former GOP lawmaker Hartzler wins 9-way contest], ''Associated Press'' (August 3, 2010).</ref>\n\nHer congressional district comprises a large swath of the western-central part of the state, anchored in [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]] and stretching to the eastern and southern [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] suburbs, including a small portion of Kansas City itself. The district also includes the cities of [[Sedalia, Missouri|Sedalia]], [[Warrensburg, Missouri|Warrensburg]], [[Moberly, Missouri|Moberly]] and [[Lebanon, Missouri|Lebanon]]. It takes in [[Fort Leonard Wood (military base)|Ft. Leonard Wood]] in [[Pulaski County, Missouri|Pulaski County]], [[Whiteman Air Force Base]] in [[Knob Noster, Missouri|Knob Noster]], as well as the [[University of Missouri]] (Mizzou).\n\n==Early years==\nHartzler was raised on a farm near [[Archie, Missouri|Archie]], a rural community south of Kansas City. She attended the [[University of Missouri]] where she graduated ''summa cum laude'' with a B.S. in Education and attended [[University of Central Missouri]] where she graduated with an M.S. in Education.<ref name=\"house.gov-biography\">[https://hartzler.house.gov/about/biography Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler biodata], hartzler.house.gov; accessed July 26, 2017</ref>\n\n==Missouri Legislature==\nBefore running for State Representative in 1994, Hartzler taught high school home economics (now commonly referred to as family and consumer sciences) for 11 years.<ref>[http://www.onenewsnow.com/Journal/stories.aspx?id=73875 Purging the pain from political campaigns] Murphree, Randall. ''OneNewsNow.com'' April 2008; accessed January 3, 2009.</ref>\n\nHer accomplishments included leadership on legislation facilitating the adoption process. Hartzler left the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] in 2000 after adopting a baby daughter. In 2004, after she had left the Missouri General Assembly, Hartzler served as state spokeswoman for the Coalition to Protect Marriage,<ref>[http://www.christianpost.com/article/20040803/missouri-begins-vote-on-same-sex-marriage-ban/index.html Missouri Begins Vote on Same-sex 'Marriage' Ban] Phan, Katherine. ''The Christian Post''. August 3, 2004. Accessed January 3, 2009</ref> which supported [[Missouri Constitutional Amendment 2 (2004)|protecting marriage in Missouri between a man and a woman]]. Despite her opposition to the Missouri Assembly's ratification of the Equal Rights Amendment<ref>{{cite web|last=Lutz|first=Jennifer|title=ERA supporters, opponents speak out|url=http://www.mdn.org/2000/STORIES/EQUAL.HTM|publisher=Missouri Digital News}}</ref> (\"I don't want women used to pass a liberal agenda\"), Republican [[Governor of Missouri|Governor]] [[Matt Blunt]] appointed Hartzler Chairwoman of the Missouri Women's Council in 2005, where she served for two years.<ref>[http://missourinet.posterous.com/former-state-rep-makes-pitch-to-replace-ike-s Former State Rep makes pitch to replace Ike Skelton in Congress] September 2, 2009; accessed January 3, 2010.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2017}}\n\n===2010===\n{{Main|2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nAfter almost a decade out of politics, Hartzler entered the Republican primary for {{ushr|MO|4}}, which at the time was held by 17-term Democratic incumbent [[Ike Skelton]]. She won a seven-way primary with 40 percent of the vote.\n\nIn the November 2, 2010 general election, Hartzler won with 50.43% of the vote. She is the first Republican to represent this district since 1955, and only the second since the [[Great Depression]]. She was also the second Republican woman elected to Congress from Missouri, after [[Jo Ann Emerson]], with whom she served from 2011 to 2013. However, she is the first who was not elected as a stand-in for her husband; Emerson was originally elected to serve out the final term of her late husband, [[Bill Emerson]]. Republicans had been making gains in the district for some time; it gave [[John McCain]] 62 percent of the vote in 2008 while simultaneously reelecting Skelton, and Republicans hold most of the district's seats in the state legislature. She won primarily by running up her totals in the more rural areas of the sprawling district.\n\nShe ran on a conservative platform, voicing support for tax cuts and spending cuts. She opposes [[abortion]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Hartzler|first=Vicky|title=Rep. Vicky Hartzler: Congress, we must protect Americans who disagree with abortion|website=Fox News|date=July 14, 2016|url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/07/14/rep-vicky-hartzler-congress-must-protect-americans-who-disagree-with-abortion.html|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> and [[same-sex marriage]].\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2010\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler \n |votes = 113,489\n |percentage = 50.43\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Ike Skelton]] (incumbent)\n |votes = 101,532\n |percentage = 45.11\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Jason Michael Braun \n |votes = 6,123\n |percentage = 2.72\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Constitution Party (United States)\n |candidate = Greg Cowan \n |votes = 3,912\n |percentage = 1.74\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2012===\n{{Main|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nRedistricting after the 2010 U.S. Census removed [[Cole County, Missouri|Cole]], [[Lafayette County, Missouri|Lafayette]], [[Ray County, Missouri|Ray]] and [[Saline County, Missouri|Saline]] counties\u2014including Skelton's home. The district also lost its shares of [[Jackson County, Missouri|Jackson]] and [[Webster County, Missouri|Webster]] counties. In its place, the district picked up all of [[Boone County, Missouri|Boone]], [[Cooper County, Missouri|Cooper]], [[Howard County, Missouri|Howard]], and [[Randolph County, Missouri|Randolph]] counties, part of [[Audrain County, Missouri|Audrain County]], and the remainder of [[Cass County, Missouri|Cass County]]. The district now includes the Cass County portion of Kansas City. The new map also pushed the district further into [[Camden County, Missouri|Camden County]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nIn her first contest in the newly drawn district, Hartzler easily won the Republican primary with 84% against Bernie Mowinski and went on to comfortably win the general election with 60.3% against Democratic [[Cass County, Missouri|Cass County]] [[Prosecutor|Prosecuting Attorney]] Teresa Hensley.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2012\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler \n |votes = 192,237\n |percentage = 60.32\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Teresa Hensley \n |votes = 113,120\n |percentage = 35.49\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Thomas Holbrook \n |votes = 10,407\n |percentage = 3.27\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Constitution Party (United States)\n |candidate = Greg Cowan \n |votes = 2,959\n |percentage = 0.93\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2014===\n{{Main|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nHartzler won nearly 75% of the party vote in the Republican congressional primary with John Webb, then went on to easily win the general election with a more than two-to-one margin.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2014\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler \n |votes = 120,014\n |percentage = 68.08\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Nate Irvin \n |votes = 46,464\n |percentage = 26.36\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Herschel L. Young \n |votes = 9,793\n |percentage = 5.56\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Write-in candidate|Write-in\n |candidate = Greg Cowan \n |votes = 15\n |percentage = 0.01\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2016===\n{{Main|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nHartzler won 72% of the party vote in the Republican congressional primary with John Webb, then won the general election with a more than two-to-one margin.\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2016\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler\n |votes = 225,348\n |percentage = 67.83\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Gordon Christensen\n |votes = 92,510\n |percentage = 27.85\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Mark Bliss\n |votes = 14,376\n |percentage = 4.33\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n=== 2018 ===\n''Main article: [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri District 4]]''{{Election box begin no change|title=Missouri's 4th congressional district, 2018}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Vicky Hartzler (incumbent)|votes=190,138|percentage=64.8}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Renee Hoagenson|votes=95,968|percentage=32.7}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Mark Bliss|votes=7,210|percentage=2.5}}\n{{Election box total no change|votes=293,316|percentage=100.0}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change|winner=Republican Party (United States)}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[116th United States Congress|116th Congress]] Committee Assignments:\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Biotechnology, Horticulture, and Research|Subcommittee on Biotechnology, Horticulture, and Research]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Livestock and Foreign Agriculture]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]], ''Ranking Member''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n\n* '''[[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]]'''\nHartzler is one of the three Republican House members serving as a commissioner. <ref>https://www.cecc.gov/members-of-116th-congress</ref>\n\nThe '''Congressional-Executive Commission on China''' ('''CECC''') is an independent agency of the [[U.S. government]] which monitors human rights and rule of law developments in the [[People's Republic of China]]. It was created in October 2001 under Title III of H.R. 4444, which authorizes normal trade relations with the PRC, and establishes a framework for relations between the two countries.<ref name=\"HR4444\">[http://www.cecc.gov/pages/general/HR4444_Title3.pdf H.R. 4444, TITLE III--CONGRESSIONAL-EXECUTIVE COMMISSION ON THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912012150/http://www.cecc.gov/pages/general/HR4444_Title3.pdf |date=2011-09-12 }}</ref> The commission was given the mandate by the [[U.S. Congress]] to monitor and report on human rights issues with a particular focus on compliance with the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] and the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]]. Its reporting covers developments in [[Freedom of speech in the People's Republic of China|freedom of expression]], the right to peaceful assembly, [[Freedom of religion in China|religious freedom]], freedom of movement, freedom from arbitrary arrest, detention, or torture, and the right to a fair trial, among others.<ref name=\"HR4444\" /> The commission publishes an annual report to the [[President of the United States]] and Congress, typically in the fall of each year. It also maintains a database of prisoners of conscience, holds regular roundtables and hearings, and issues letters to other institutions concerning human rights matters.<ref name=\"CECC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cecc.gov/index.php|title=Congressional-Executive Commission on China|website=www.cecc.gov|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cecc.gov/media-center/press-releases/xinjiang-chairs-ask-whether-world-bank-funding-crimes-against-humanity|title=Xinjiang: Chairs Ask Whether World Bank Funding Possible \"Crimes Against Humanity\"|date=August 23, 2019|website=[[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]]|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n*'''[[Republican Study Committee|Value Actions Team]]'''\nSince the 115th Congress, Hartzler has served as the Chairwoman of the Value Actions Team, a subcommittee within the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>https://hartzler.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/hartzler-takes-helm-house-values-action-team</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Hartzler was named to serve on the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce Select Investigative Panel on Planned Parenthood|Select Investigative Panel on Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/10/23/boehners-next-select-committee-focusing-on-planned-parenthood-to-be-led-by-marsha-blackburn|title=Boehner's next select committee, focusing on Planned Parenthood, to be led by Marsha Blackburn|author=Paul Kane|date=October 23, 2015|work=Washington Post|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Caucuses===\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov|publisher=Republican Study Committee|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n* Congressional Cement Caucus\n* [[Veterinary Medicine Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Veterinary Medicine Caucus|author=|url=https://schrader.house.gov/committees/veterinary-medicine-caucus.htm| publisher=Veterinary Medicine Caucus |date=|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nHartzler is facing a complaint that she violated congressional ethics rules by tweeting an image from her Congressional account promoting Case IH\u2019s products, which are manufactured by Hartzler\u2019s personal business, Heartland Tractor Company.<ref>https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article233706162.html</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Abortion===\nHartzler is an outspoken opponent of [[abortion]].<ref name=\"house.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://hartzler.house.gov/legislative-work/issues/marriage-and-life|title=Marriage and Life|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"kansascity.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article129481594.html|title=Missouri, Kansas politicians weigh in on Trump immigration ban|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref> In January 2020, it was reported that Hartzler is one of 207 members of congress that asked SCOTUS to consider overruling Roe V. Wade.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===LGBT rights===\nHartzler strongly opposes [[same-sex marriage]], [[civil union]]s, and [[domestic partnership]]s.<ref name=\"house.gov\"/> She also opposes banning [[discrimination]] based on [[sexual orientation]] and [[gender identity]]. In 2019, Hartzler expressed her strong opposition to the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]].<ref>{{cite news |title=House Debate on the Equality Act |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?460685-3/house-debate-equality-act |work=[[C-SPAN]] |date=May 17, 2019}}</ref> She also opposes allowing transgender individuals to serve in the military.<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2017/07/26/politics/transgender-military-ban-vicky-hartzler-cnntv/index.html</ref><ref>[https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/11/02/republican-congresswoman-vicky-hartzler-not-sorry-gay-cure-therapy-links/ Republican congresswoman Vicky Hartzler is not sorry for promoting gay cure therapy]</ref>  Hartzler opposes [[transsexualism]].\n\n===Military===\nOn June 29, 2017 Hartzler opposed allowing transgender Americans to serve in the U.S. armed forces, and proposed an amendment to the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2018 to reverse an Obama-administration policy that allowed transgender Americans in the armed services.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hartzler.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/hartzler-statement-ndaa-amendment-reverse-obama-transgender-policy|title=Hartzler Statement on NDAA Amendment to Reverse Obama Transgender Policy|date=June 29, 2017|work=Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler|access-date=July 19, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Hartzler's amendment was rejected in a 209-214 vote,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lardner|first1=Richard|title=House rejects attempt to ban transgender surgery for troops|url=https://apnews.com/42543881d87246c0aad086ebade752c5|website=Associated Press|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=H.Amdt.183 to H.R.2810 in 115th Congress (2017-2018)|url=https://www.congress.gov/amendment/115th-congress/house-amendment/183/actions|website=Congress.gov|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> but Trump subsequently announced that he would [[Directive-type Memorandum-19-004|ban transgender people]] to serve in U.S. military; Hartzler said that she was \"very pleased\" with the decision.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lowry|first1=Brian|title=Trump blocking transgender troops comes after pressure from Missouri's Vicky Hartzler|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article163693263.html|website=The Kansas City Star|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Women===\nHartzler voted against the reauthorization of the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Vicky_Hartzler.htm|title=Vicky Hartzler on the Issues|last=OnTheIssues.org|website=www.ontheissues.org|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Barack Obama===\nAt a town hall meeting in Missouri on April 5, 2012, Hartzler expressed doubts regarding President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|birth certificate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/06/vicki-hartzler-birther_n_1409082.html|title=Obama Birth Certificate: Missouri Congresswoman Vicki Hartzler Expresses Doubt|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=April 6, 2012|first=John|last=Celock}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nHartzler is a staunch opponent of the [[Affordable Care Act]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Vicky_Hartzler_Health_Care.htm|title=Vicky Hartzler on Health Care|website=ontheissues.org|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref> and a supporter of the [[American Health Care Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbo.gov/system/files/115th-congress-2017-2018/costestimate/americanhealthcareact.pdf |format=PDF |title=American Health Care Act |website=Cbo.gov |accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Agriculture===\nIn September 2013, Hartzler voted in favor of a $39 billion reduction in [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program]] (SNAP) Benefits (aka \"food stamps\"). This bill was separate for the first time in over three decades from [[Agricultural subsidy#United States|farm subsidies]], which were increased.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-23/how-republicans-justify-cutting-food-stamps-while-boosting-farm-subsidies.html|title=How Republicans Justify Cutting Food Stamps While Boosting Farm Subsidies|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In 2018, Hartzler again supported a farm subsidy bill.<ref>[https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article213687999.html] Article in ''The Kansas City Star'']</ref>\n\n===Environment===\nHartzler rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. On November 18, 2014, during the worst early season cold snap in the U.S. since 1976, Hartzler made a joke about [[climate change]] on [[Twitter]]. \"Global warming strikes America! Brrrr!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RepHartzler/status/534688626484183040|title=Global warming strikes America! Brrrr!|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> The quip was rebutted in detail by ''[[The Washington Post]]'', which reported that her district in Missouri is among the areas most severely impacted by climate change in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/11/18/congresswoman-vicky-hartzler-wonders-why-its-so-cold-if-global-warming-exists-heres-the-answer|title=Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler wonders why it's so cold if global warming exists. Here's the answer.|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe voted to approve the construction of the [[Keystone XL Pipeline]] on the federally protected lands of Indigenous people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/bill/19390/50944/8783/a-bill-to-approve-the-keystone-xl-pipeline|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nIn February 2016, during a trip to [[Israel]], Hartzler voiced her support for the country and shared the belief that \"our country has been blessed because we have been a blessing to Israel\".<ref>{{cite web | last=Lazaroff | first=Tovah | title=Visiting GOP congressman from Florida: Israel has done its utmost to promote peace | website=The Jerusalem Post &#124; JPost.com | date=February 23, 2016 | url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Visiting-GOP-congressman-from-Florida-Israel-has-done-its-utmost-to-promote-peace-445783 | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nIn January 2017, Hartzler made a statement supporting President [[Donald J Trump]]'s ban on immigrants from seven Muslim countries and halting the U.S. Refugee program for 120 days.<ref name=\"kansascity.com\"/> In her statement, Hartzler drew equivalency between Trump's executive order and Obama's 2011 policy that slowed immigration from Iraq by saying they were \"similar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/big-differences-between-trumps-immigration-ban-obamas-2011-policy-2017-2|title=There are major differences between Trump's immigration ban and Obama's 2011 policy|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Hartzler supported Trump's rollback of the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hartzler.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/statement-president-trump-s-executive-order-fiduciary-rule|title=Statement on President Trump's Executive Order on Fiduciary Rule|date=February 3, 2017|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Guns===\nHartzler opposes gun control and advocates for looser gun laws. She is a staunch supporter of the Second Amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Vicky_Hartzler_Gun_Control.htm|title=Vicky Hartzler on Gun Control|website=ontheissues.org|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHartzler lives on a farm near [[Harrisonville, Missouri|Harrisonville]] with her family.<ref name=\"house.gov-biography\" /> According to publicly available data reviewed by the Kansas City Star, Hartzler, with her family farm, has been one of the biggest beneficiaries of federal farm subsidies out of all members of Congress, receiving $995,498 between 1995 and 2016.\n\n==Works==\n* Vicky Hartzler self-published the book ''Running God's Way'', Pleasant Word (a division of the now defunct WinePress Publishing; December 13, 2007); {{ISBN|978-1-4141-1124-7}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hartzler.house.gov/ Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler] official U.S. House site\n* [http://vickyhartzler.com/ Vicky Hartzler for Congress]\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Missouri/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Vicky_Hartzler_%5BR-4%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=H001053 | votesmart=8783 | fec=H0MO04086 | congress=vicky-hartzler/2032 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ike Skelton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Missouri's 4th congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andy Harris (politician)|Andy Harris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=163rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jaime Herrera Beutler]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MO-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hartzler, Vicky}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Educators from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Female members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Leadership Institute alumni and associates]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Missouri House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Missouri Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Harrisonville, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:University of Central Missouri alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Missouri alumni]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Missouri]]\n[[Category:American gun rights activists]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Vicky Hartzler\n|image        = [[File:Vicky Hartzler 116th Congress.jpg|thumb]]\n|state        = [[Missouri]]\n|district     = {{ushr|MO|4|4th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Ike Skelton]]\n|successor    = \n|state_house1 = Missouri\n|district1    = 124th\n|term_start1  = 1995\n|term_end1    = 2000\n|predecessor1 = Gene Olson\n|successor1   = Rex Rector\n|birth_name   = Vicky Jo Zellmer\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1960|10|13}}\n|birth_place  = [[Archie, Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lowell Hartzler\n|children     = 1 daughter\n|education    = [[University of Missouri]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Central Missouri]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n'''Vicky Jo Hartzler''' (n\u00e9e '''Zellmer''', October 13, 1960) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MO|4}} since 2011. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], she previously served as the [[Missouri House of Representatives|Missouri State Representative]] for the 124th district from 1995 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legistorm.com/memberbio/2769/Rep_Vicky_Hartzler_MO.html|title=Representative Vicky Jo Hartzler (Vicky) (R-Missouri, 4th) \u2013 Biography from LegiStorm|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.fox4kc.com/news/sns-ap-mo--missouricongress-4thdistrict,0,6855380.story Former GOP lawmaker Hartzler wins 9-way contest], ''Associated Press'' (August 3, 2010).</ref>\n\nHer congressional district comprises a large swath of the western-central part of the state, anchored in [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]] and stretching to the eastern and southern [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] suburbs, including a small portion of Kansas City itself. The district also includes the cities of [[Sedalia, Missouri|Sedalia]], [[Warrensburg, Missouri|Warrensburg]], [[Moberly, Missouri|Moberly]] and [[Lebanon, Missouri|Lebanon]]. It takes in [[Fort Leonard Wood (military base)|Ft. Leonard Wood]] in [[Pulaski County, Missouri|Pulaski County]], [[Whiteman Air Force Base]] in [[Knob Noster, Missouri|Knob Noster]], as well as the [[University of Missouri]] (Mizzou).\n\n==Early years==\nHartzler was raised on a farm near [[Archie, Missouri|Archie]], a rural community south of Kansas City. She attended the [[University of Missouri]] where she graduated ''summa cum laude'' with a B.S. in Education and attended [[University of Central Missouri]] where she graduated with an M.S. in Education.<ref name=\"house.gov-biography\">[https://hartzler.house.gov/about/biography Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler biodata], hartzler.house.gov; accessed July 26, 2017</ref>\n\n==Missouri Legislature==\nBefore running for State Representative in 1994, Hartzler taught high school home economics (now commonly referred to as family and consumer sciences) for 11 years.<ref>[http://www.onenewsnow.com/Journal/stories.aspx?id=73875 Purging the pain from political campaigns] Murphree, Randall. ''OneNewsNow.com'' April 2008; accessed January 3, 2009.</ref>\n\nHer accomplishments included leadership on legislation facilitating the adoption process. Hartzler left the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] in 2000 after adopting a baby daughter. In 2004, after she had left the Missouri General Assembly, Hartzler served as state spokeswoman for the Coalition to Protect Marriage,<ref>[http://www.christianpost.com/article/20040803/missouri-begins-vote-on-same-sex-marriage-ban/index.html Missouri Begins Vote on Same-sex 'Marriage' Ban] Phan, Katherine. ''The Christian Post''. August 3, 2004. Accessed January 3, 2009</ref> which supported [[Missouri Constitutional Amendment 2 (2004)|protecting marriage in Missouri between a man and a woman]]. Despite her opposition to the Missouri Assembly's ratification of the Equal Rights Amendment<ref>{{cite web|last=Lutz|first=Jennifer|title=ERA supporters, opponents speak out|url=http://www.mdn.org/2000/STORIES/EQUAL.HTM|publisher=Missouri Digital News}}</ref> (\"I don't want women used to pass a liberal agenda\"), Republican [[Governor of Missouri|Governor]] [[Matt Blunt]] appointed Hartzler Chairwoman of the Missouri Women's Council in 2005, where she served for two years.<ref>[http://missourinet.posterous.com/former-state-rep-makes-pitch-to-replace-ike-s Former State Rep makes pitch to replace Ike Skelton in Congress] September 2, 2009; accessed January 3, 2010.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2017}}\n\n===2010===\n{{Main|2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nAfter almost a decade out of politics, Hartzler entered the Republican primary for {{ushr|MO|4}}, which at the time was held by 17-term Democratic incumbent [[Ike Skelton]]. She won a seven-way primary with 40 percent of the vote.\n\nIn the November 2, 2010 general election, Hartzler won with 50.43% of the vote. She is the first Republican to represent this district since 1955, and only the second since the [[Great Depression]]. She was also the second Republican woman elected to Congress from Missouri, after [[Jo Ann Emerson]], with whom she served from 2011 to 2013. However, she is the first who was not elected as a stand-in for her husband; Emerson was originally elected to serve out the final term of her late husband, [[Bill Emerson]]. Republicans had been making gains in the district for some time; it gave [[John McCain]] 62 percent of the vote in 2008 while simultaneously reelecting Skelton, and Republicans hold most of the district's seats in the state legislature. She won primarily by running up her totals in the more rural areas of the sprawling district.\n\nShe ran on a conservative platform, voicing support for tax cuts and spending cuts. She opposes [[abortion]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Hartzler|first=Vicky|title=Rep. Vicky Hartzler: Congress, we must protect Americans who disagree with abortion|website=Fox News|date=July 14, 2016|url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/07/14/rep-vicky-hartzler-congress-must-protect-americans-who-disagree-with-abortion.html|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> and [[same-sex marriage]].\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2010\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler \n |votes = 113,489\n |percentage = 50.43\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Ike Skelton]] (incumbent)\n |votes = 101,532\n |percentage = 45.11\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Jason Michael Braun \n |votes = 6,123\n |percentage = 2.72\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Constitution Party (United States)\n |candidate = Greg Cowan \n |votes = 3,912\n |percentage = 1.74\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2012===\n{{Main|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nRedistricting after the 2010 U.S. Census removed [[Cole County, Missouri|Cole]], [[Lafayette County, Missouri|Lafayette]], [[Ray County, Missouri|Ray]] and [[Saline County, Missouri|Saline]] counties\u2014including Skelton's home. The district also lost its shares of [[Jackson County, Missouri|Jackson]] and [[Webster County, Missouri|Webster]] counties. In its place, the district picked up all of [[Boone County, Missouri|Boone]], [[Cooper County, Missouri|Cooper]], [[Howard County, Missouri|Howard]], and [[Randolph County, Missouri|Randolph]] counties, part of [[Audrain County, Missouri|Audrain County]], and the remainder of [[Cass County, Missouri|Cass County]]. The district now includes the Cass County portion of Kansas City. The new map also pushed the district further into [[Camden County, Missouri|Camden County]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nIn her first contest in the newly drawn district, Hartzler easily won the Republican primary with 84% against Bernie Mowinski and went on to comfortably win the general election with 60.3% against Democratic [[Cass County, Missouri|Cass County]] [[Prosecutor|Prosecuting Attorney]] Teresa Hensley.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2012\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler \n |votes = 192,237\n |percentage = 60.32\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Teresa Hensley \n |votes = 113,120\n |percentage = 35.49\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Thomas Holbrook \n |votes = 10,407\n |percentage = 3.27\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Constitution Party (United States)\n |candidate = Greg Cowan \n |votes = 2,959\n |percentage = 0.93\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2014===\n{{Main|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nHartzler won nearly 75% of the party vote in the Republican congressional primary with John Webb, then went on to easily win the general election with a more than two-to-one margin.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2014\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler \n |votes = 120,014\n |percentage = 68.08\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Nate Irvin \n |votes = 46,464\n |percentage = 26.36\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Herschel L. Young \n |votes = 9,793\n |percentage = 5.56\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Write-in candidate|Write-in\n |candidate = Greg Cowan \n |votes = 15\n |percentage = 0.01\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2016===\n{{Main|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri#District 4}}\nHartzler won 72% of the party vote in the Republican congressional primary with John Webb, then won the general election with a more than two-to-one margin.\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Missouri\u2019s 4th congressional district election, 2016\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Vicky Hartzler\n |votes = 225,348\n |percentage = 67.83\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Gordon Christensen\n |votes = 92,510\n |percentage = 27.85\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n |candidate = Mark Bliss\n |votes = 14,376\n |percentage = 4.33\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n=== 2018 ===\n''Main article: [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Missouri District 4]]''{{Election box begin no change|title=Missouri's 4th congressional district, 2018}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Vicky Hartzler (incumbent)|votes=190,138|percentage=64.8}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Renee Hoagenson|votes=95,968|percentage=32.7}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Mark Bliss|votes=7,210|percentage=2.5}}\n{{Election box total no change|votes=293,316|percentage=100.0}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change|winner=Republican Party (United States)}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[116th United States Congress|116th Congress]] Committee Assignments:\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Biotechnology, Horticulture, and Research|Subcommittee on Biotechnology, Horticulture, and Research]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Livestock and Foreign Agriculture]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]], ''Ranking Member''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n\n* '''[[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]]'''\nHartzler is one of the three Republican House members serving as a commissioner. <ref>https://www.cecc.gov/members-of-116th-congress</ref>\n\nThe '''Congressional-Executive Commission on China''' ('''CECC''') is an independent agency of the [[U.S. government]] which monitors human rights and rule of law developments in the [[People's Republic of China]]. It was created in October 2001 under Title III of H.R. 4444, which authorizes normal trade relations with the PRC, and establishes a framework for relations between the two countries.<ref name=\"HR4444\">[http://www.cecc.gov/pages/general/HR4444_Title3.pdf H.R. 4444, TITLE III--CONGRESSIONAL-EXECUTIVE COMMISSION ON THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912012150/http://www.cecc.gov/pages/general/HR4444_Title3.pdf |date=2011-09-12 }}</ref> The commission was given the mandate by the [[U.S. Congress]] to monitor and report on human rights issues with a particular focus on compliance with the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] and the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]]. Its reporting covers developments in [[Freedom of speech in the People's Republic of China|freedom of expression]], the right to peaceful assembly, [[Freedom of religion in China|religious freedom]], freedom of movement, freedom from arbitrary arrest, detention, or torture, and the right to a fair trial, among others.<ref name=\"HR4444\" /> The commission publishes an annual report to the [[President of the United States]] and Congress, typically in the fall of each year. It also maintains a database of prisoners of conscience, holds regular roundtables and hearings, and issues letters to other institutions concerning human rights matters.<ref name=\"CECC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cecc.gov/index.php|title=Congressional-Executive Commission on China|website=www.cecc.gov|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cecc.gov/media-center/press-releases/xinjiang-chairs-ask-whether-world-bank-funding-crimes-against-humanity|title=Xinjiang: Chairs Ask Whether World Bank Funding Possible \"Crimes Against Humanity\"|date=August 23, 2019|website=[[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]]|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n*'''[[Republican Study Committee|Value Actions Team]]'''\nSince the 115th Congress, Hartzler has served as the Chairwoman of the Value Actions Team, a subcommittee within the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>https://hartzler.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/hartzler-takes-helm-house-values-action-team</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Hartzler was named to serve on the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce Select Investigative Panel on Planned Parenthood|Select Investigative Panel on Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/10/23/boehners-next-select-committee-focusing-on-planned-parenthood-to-be-led-by-marsha-blackburn|title=Boehner's next select committee, focusing on Planned Parenthood, to be led by Marsha Blackburn|author=Paul Kane|date=October 23, 2015|work=Washington Post|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Caucuses===\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov|publisher=Republican Study Committee|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n* Congressional Cement Caucus\n* [[Veterinary Medicine Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Veterinary Medicine Caucus|author=|url=https://schrader.house.gov/committees/veterinary-medicine-caucus.htm| publisher=Veterinary Medicine Caucus |date=|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nHartzler is facing a complaint that she violated congressional ethics rules by tweeting an image from her Congressional account promoting Case IH\u2019s products, which are manufactured by Hartzler\u2019s personal business, Heartland Tractor Company.<ref>https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article233706162.html</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Abortion===\nHartzler is an outspoken opponent of [[abortion]].<ref name=\"house.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://hartzler.house.gov/legislative-work/issues/marriage-and-life|title=Marriage and Life|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"kansascity.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article129481594.html|title=Missouri, Kansas politicians weigh in on Trump immigration ban|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref> In January 2020, it was reported that Hartzler is one of 207 members of congress that asked SCOTUS to consider overruling Roe V. Wade.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===LGBT rights===\nHartzler strongly opposes [[same-sex marriage]], [[civil union]]s, and [[domestic partnership]]s.<ref name=\"house.gov\"/> She also opposes banning [[discrimination]] based on [[sexual orientation]] and [[gender identity]]. In 2019, Hartzler expressed her strong opposition to the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]].<ref>{{cite news |title=House Debate on the Equality Act |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?460685-3/house-debate-equality-act |work=[[C-SPAN]] |date=May 17, 2019}}</ref> She also opposes allowing transgender individuals to serve in the military.<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2017/07/26/politics/transgender-military-ban-vicky-hartzler-cnntv/index.html</ref><ref>[https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/11/02/republican-congresswoman-vicky-hartzler-not-sorry-gay-cure-therapy-links/ Republican congresswoman Vicky Hartzler is not sorry for promoting gay cure therapy]</ref>  Hartzler opposes [[transsexualism]].\n\n===Military===\nOn June 29, 2017 Hartzler opposed allowing transgender Americans to serve in the U.S. armed forces, and proposed an amendment to the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2018 to reverse an Obama-administration policy that allowed transgender Americans in the armed services.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hartzler.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/hartzler-statement-ndaa-amendment-reverse-obama-transgender-policy|title=Hartzler Statement on NDAA Amendment to Reverse Obama Transgender Policy|date=June 29, 2017|work=Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler|access-date=July 19, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Hartzler's amendment was rejected in a 209-214 vote,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lardner|first1=Richard|title=House rejects attempt to ban transgender surgery for troops|url=https://apnews.com/42543881d87246c0aad086ebade752c5|website=Associated Press|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=H.Amdt.183 to H.R.2810 in 115th Congress (2017-2018)|url=https://www.congress.gov/amendment/115th-congress/house-amendment/183/actions|website=Congress.gov|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> but Trump subsequently announced that he would [[Directive-type Memorandum-19-004|ban transgender people]] to serve in U.S. military; Hartzler said that she was \"very pleased\" with the decision.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lowry|first1=Brian|title=Trump blocking transgender troops comes after pressure from Missouri's Vicky Hartzler|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article163693263.html|website=The Kansas City Star|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Women===\nHartzler voted against the reauthorization of the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Vicky_Hartzler.htm|title=Vicky Hartzler on the Issues|last=OnTheIssues.org|website=www.ontheissues.org|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Barack Obama===\nAt a town hall meeting in Missouri on April 5, 2012, Hartzler expressed doubts regarding President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|birth certificate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/06/vicki-hartzler-birther_n_1409082.html|title=Obama Birth Certificate: Missouri Congresswoman Vicki Hartzler Expresses Doubt|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=April 6, 2012|first=John|last=Celock}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nHartzler is a staunch opponent of the [[Affordable Care Act]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Vicky_Hartzler_Health_Care.htm|title=Vicky Hartzler on Health Care|website=ontheissues.org|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref> and a supporter of the [[American Health Care Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbo.gov/system/files/115th-congress-2017-2018/costestimate/americanhealthcareact.pdf |format=PDF |title=American Health Care Act |website=Cbo.gov |accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Agriculture===\nIn September 2013, Hartzler voted in favor of a $39 billion reduction in [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program]] (SNAP) Benefits (aka \"food stamps\"). This bill was separate for the first time in over three decades from [[Agricultural subsidy#United States|farm subsidies]], which were increased.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-23/how-republicans-justify-cutting-food-stamps-while-boosting-farm-subsidies.html|title=How Republicans Justify Cutting Food Stamps While Boosting Farm Subsidies|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In 2018, Hartzler again supported a farm subsidy bill.<ref>[https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article213687999.html] Article in ''The Kansas City Star'']</ref>\n\n===Environment===\nHartzler rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. On November 18, 2014, during the worst early season cold snap in the U.S. since 1976, Hartzler made a joke about [[climate change]] on [[Twitter]]. \"Global warming strikes America! Brrrr!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RepHartzler/status/534688626484183040|title=Global warming strikes America! Brrrr!|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> The quip was rebutted in detail by ''[[The Washington Post]]'', which reported that her district in Missouri is among the areas most severely impacted by climate change in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/11/18/congresswoman-vicky-hartzler-wonders-why-its-so-cold-if-global-warming-exists-heres-the-answer|title=Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler wonders why it's so cold if global warming exists. Here's the answer.|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe voted to approve the construction of the [[Keystone XL Pipeline]] on the federally protected lands of Indigenous people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/bill/19390/50944/8783/a-bill-to-approve-the-keystone-xl-pipeline|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nIn February 2016, during a trip to [[Israel]], Hartzler voiced her support for the country and shared the belief that \"our country has been blessed because we have been a blessing to Israel\".<ref>{{cite web | last=Lazaroff | first=Tovah | title=Visiting GOP congressman from Florida: Israel has done its utmost to promote peace | website=The Jerusalem Post &#124; JPost.com | date=February 23, 2016 | url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Visiting-GOP-congressman-from-Florida-Israel-has-done-its-utmost-to-promote-peace-445783 | access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nIn January 2017, Hartzler made a statement supporting President [[Donald J Trump]]'s ban on immigrants from seven Muslim countries and halting the U.S. Refugee program for 120 days.<ref name=\"kansascity.com\"/> In her statement, Hartzler drew equivalency between Trump's executive order and Obama's 2011 policy that slowed immigration from Iraq by saying they were \"similar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/big-differences-between-trumps-immigration-ban-obamas-2011-policy-2017-2|title=There are major differences between Trump's immigration ban and Obama's 2011 policy|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Hartzler supported Trump's rollback of the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hartzler.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/statement-president-trump-s-executive-order-fiduciary-rule|title=Statement on President Trump's Executive Order on Fiduciary Rule|date=February 3, 2017|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Guns===\nHartzler opposes gun control and advocates for looser gun laws. She is a staunch supporter of the Second Amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Vicky_Hartzler_Gun_Control.htm|title=Vicky Hartzler on Gun Control|website=ontheissues.org|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHartzler lives on a farm near [[Harrisonville, Missouri|Harrisonville]] with her family.<ref name=\"house.gov-biography\" /> According to publicly available data reviewed by the Kansas City Star, Hartzler, with her family farm, has been one of the biggest beneficiaries of federal farm subsidies out of all members of Congress, receiving $995,498 between 1995 and 2016.\n\n==Works==\n* Vicky Hartzler self-published the book ''Running God's Way'', Pleasant Word (a division of the now defunct WinePress Publishing; December 13, 2007); {{ISBN|978-1-4141-1124-7}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hartzler.house.gov/ Congresswoman Vicky Hartzler] official U.S. House site\n* [http://vickyhartzler.com/ Vicky Hartzler for Congress]\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Missouri/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Vicky_Hartzler_%5BR-4%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=H001053 | votesmart=8783 | fec=H0MO04086 | congress=vicky-hartzler/2032 }}\